oakcurric:unit-995
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Minor, major and developing keyboard skills"@en ;
  curric:slug "minor-major-and-developing-keyboard-skills" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces major and minor scales and explores what makes music
  distinctive and memorable. Pupils develop keyboard technique and rehearsal strateiges,
  learning more complex melodic lines with accidentals and varied articulation."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils develop keyboard technique, becoming more fluent in moving out of
  position, playing the black keys, and playing longer, more complex melodic lines and broken
  chords. They develop their ability to perform expressively in more advanced keyboard music,
  including using rubato. They explore melodic techniques such as sequence and anacrusis and
  the importance of phrase structure. They start to understand the importanace of the third in
  defining keys and how scales work. They develop their own creative ideas using other music as
  inspiration, learning more about what makes a piece successful.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-995-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-995-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-995-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-995-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-995-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-995-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-995-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-995-8 ;
  curric:id "995"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.053769Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-r ,
    oakcurric:thread-instrumental-fluency ,
    oakcurric:thread-expressive-elements .

oakcurric:unit-3802
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Folk songs from around the world"@en ;
  curric:slug "folk-songs-from-around-the-world" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores folk music from around the world, with detailed looks at sea
  shanties and Russian folk dance. Pupils are exposed to a diverse array of folk music,
  exploring characteristics that are typical of folk traditions, composing simple melodies,
  singing and performing using keyboards."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about the folk song tradition, continuing to learn about the
  pentatonic scale and modes as a compositional starting point. They sing songs changing from
  unison to harmony passages and the impact this can have. They develop keyboard skills,
  learning to move out of position within a phrase, learning the notes outside C to C and
  reinforcing their understanding of crotchet, quavers and dotted rhythms. They learn about
  folk instruments outside of the orchestra and about alternative structures to ABA form. They
  also consider lyric writing and the relationship between lyrics and rhythm.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3802-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3802-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3802-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3802-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3802-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3802-6 ;
  curric:id "3802"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.356549Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-1008
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The 12-bar blues"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-blues" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the 12-bar blues, the stylistic and musical
  features of blues music and the role of the instruments in a blues ensemble. They develop
  an extended improvisation and build a stylistic blues performance."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn to play the 12-bar blues in a range of different ways,
  including improvising with the blues scale and the boogie-woogie pattern. They develop their
  keyboard skills, learning about and how to play chords, using the blues scale to improvise
  within a fixed but more extended structure and playing more independent and syncopated parts
  on the keyboard. They develop their understanding of instruments, the role they play and the
  impact they have on the music.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1008-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1008-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1008-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1008-4 ;
  curric:id "1008"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.613239Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-r ,
    oakcurric:thread-instrumental-fluency ,
    oakcurric:thread-composing-and-improvising ,
    oakcurric:thread-drum-grooves ,
    oakcurric:thread-improvisation ,
    oakcurric:thread-harmony ,
    oakcurric:thread-daw .

oakcurric:unit-3867
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Year 9 song guides"@en ;
  curric:slug "year-9-song-guides" ;
  rdfs:comment """The song guides cover a diverse selection of songs, designed to develop vocal
  technique, musical expression and ensemble skills, and building confidence and musical
  literacy. They can be broken down across multiple lessons to integrate them into the
  sequence, but can also be taught as full lessons."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """These song guides focus on learning and performing two songs, with
  opportunities to explore melody, rhythm, harmony and style. Specifically, pupils develop
  their understanding of singing in more complex textures, creating a harmonious ensemble
  sound, shaping a melody and breath control.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3867-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3867-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3867-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3867-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3867-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3867-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3867-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3867-8 ;
  curric:id "3867"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.844134Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-3713
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Approaches to contemporary composition"@en ;
  curric:slug "approaches-to-contemporary-composition" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils are introduced to contemporary compositional approaches and
  techniques. They learn about a range of current contemporary music and the differences in
  approach of how this is structured and put together from earlier classical style music and
  current popular music."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils develop their understanding of musical starting points in
  composing, learning about what might stimulate musical ideas in contemporary music and how
  unity and variety can be found with more abstract musical ideas. They learn about the use of
  the voice, and SATB vocal lines and develop harmonic understanding of dissonance and
  consonance and the tone row as a musical starting point. They extend their understanding of
  how sampling can be used musically.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3713-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3713-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3713-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3713-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3713-5 ;
  curric:id "3713"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.972274Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-3839
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Djembe drumming and rhythms from the regions of West Africa"@en ;
  curric:slug "djembe-drumming-and-rhythms-from-the-regions-of-west-africa" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils are introduced to drumming from the regions of West Africa, performing as
  an ensemble and developing their understanding of djembe technique, the structure and
  musical conventions of the music, how rhythm and tempo are used to create excitement and
  the culture connected with the music."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils develop their ensemble skills and rhythmic understanding,
  performing and composing in extended structures, 12/8 time signatures and multiple rhythmic
  parts, allowing for part switching between more complex rhythms. They develop their
  understanding of syncopation though aural copying and grid notation, creating their own
  piece, focusing on rhythmic elements, with opportunity to build more complex polyrhythms and
  improvise extended rhythmic ideas. They learn the key instruments and technique of drumming
  from the regions of West Africa. Body percussion can be used instead of djembes.""" ;
  curric:id "3839"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.130969Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-3803
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Year 8 song guides"@en ;
  curric:slug "year-8-song-guides" ;
  rdfs:comment """The song guides cover a diverse selection of songs, designed to develop vocal
  technique, musical expression and ensemble skills, and building confidence and musical
  literacy. They can be broken down across multiple lessons to integrate them into the
  sequence, but can also be taught as full lessons."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """These song guides focus on learning and performing two songs, with
  opportunities to explore melody, rhythm, harmony and style. Specifically, pupils develop
  their understanding of warming up the body for singing, developing their understanding of
  balance and tone quality, singing in three part harmony and how rhythm and emphasis in the
  phrase can have an impact on the feel of a performance.""" ;
  curric:id "3803"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.147213Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-997
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "EDM remixing"@en ;
  curric:slug "harmonic-rhythm-off-beats-and-idiomatic-timbre-in-edm" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about EDM (electronic dance music), the main features
  of the style and the impact these features have on creating excitement in the music and a
  danceable groove. They learn about arranging through creating a remix of a famous melody."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit extends pupils’ understanding of pop drum grooves and bass
  patterns, while further developing confidence and creativity when working with a DAW. Pupils
  focus on drum grooves, particularly four-on-the-floor, and on composing syncopated basslines,
  widening their understanding of key pop music features. They explore arranging techniques and
  learn to use DAW tools such as risers, EQ and volume automation to create effective
  build-ups, contrast and climactic moments in their music.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-997-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-997-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-997-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-997-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-997-5 ;
  curric:id "997"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.667816Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-r ,
    oakcurric:thread-composing-and-improvising ,
    oakcurric:thread-drum-grooves ,
    oakcurric:thread-improvisation ,
    oakcurric:thread-harmony .

oakcurric:unit-3833
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Taiko drumming"@en ;
  curric:slug "taiko-drumming" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils are introduced to Taiko drumming, performing as an ensemble, composing in
  groups and learning about the energy that pulse and rhythm can bring to a performance.
  They learn the key terminology and technique of Taiko and develop an understanding of the
  culture connected with the music."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils continue to enjoy making music in groups and explore extended
  structures for performance and composition. They develop their understanding of rhythm and
  its relationship with pulse and are introduced to shuffle feel. They build on prior skills
  with ensemble performance and create their own piece, with a focus on rhythmic elements,
  including silence and creative movement, within a style that offers scaffolded structures and
  rhythmic ideas. Pupils continue to learn about the importance of correct technique in
  performance. Tasks can use percussion, practice pads or chair drumming.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3833-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3833-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3833-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3833-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3833-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3833-6 ;
  curric:id "3833"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.916387Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-1154
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Atmospheric music"@en ;
  curric:slug "atmospheric-music" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils learn about programmatic and descriptive music and how music can be used to
  set the scene. They compose a piece of music to accompany a story that includes a
  recurring motif and demonstrates an understanding of how key/chromatics and other musical
  elements can have an impact on the mood."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit develops pupils’ understanding of how musical ideas are created,
  shaped and developed through the use of motifs and ostinati, alongside devices such as pedal
  notes, trills and chromatic movement. Pupils explore the elements of music and instrumental
  techniques, including instrumental clichés, to understand how instruments are used
  effectively and in style. They learn how key, a sense of home note, timbre and chromatic
  movement influence mood and atmosphere, and what makes an idea sound convincingly musical in
  their own compositions.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1154-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1154-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1154-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1154-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1154-5 ;
  curric:id "1154"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.333380Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-992
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Harmonic progressions and bass lines"@en ;
  curric:slug "harmonic-progressions-bass-lines-and-shuffle" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils extend their understanding of harmonic progressions, learning
  about ground bass and triadic harmony."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils extend their keyboard skills, focussing on developing the left hand
  and left hand accompaniment patterns. They learn how to identify notes in the bass clef
  through performance. They further develop their understanding of harmony, including learning
  about triadic harmony, how to build melodies and musical ideas with chordal harmony as a
  starting point, passing notes and the impact of the tonic and dominant notes of the scale.
  They continue to learn about how they can develop their musical ideas.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-992-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-992-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-992-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-992-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-992-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-992-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-992-7 ;
  curric:id "992"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.971430Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-r ,
    oakcurric:thread-instrumental-fluency ,
    oakcurric:thread-expressive-elements .

oakcurric:unit-979
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Making music together"@en ;
  curric:slug "making-music-together" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit develops pupils’ confidence and enjoyment in making music, encouraging
  them to see themselves as musicians. They sing as a group, develop composition skills, and
  revisit key musical terms to engage thoughtfully with the elements of music and use them
  creatively and expressively."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils are introduced to key musical terms allowing them to
  meaningfully interact with a range of different music. They build on prior skills with
  singing and composing, performing a song together as a group, exploring pulse and continuing
  to learn how to prepare and develop the voice for performance. They compose a piece of music
  to a stimulus experimenting with how they can use the elements of music creatively and
  effectively. There are a range of listening, performance and composition based tasks to allow
  appropriate measurement of attainment and progress.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-979-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-979-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-979-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-979-4 ;
  curric:id "979"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.083945Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-melody ,
    oakcurric:thread-expressive-elements ,
    oakcurric:thread-our-singing-voice .

oakcurric:unit-981
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Fundamental drum grooves"@en ;
  curric:slug "fundamental-drum-grooves" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to the DAW as a composition tool and the fundamental
  features of a simple rock beat. They learn about the importance of a balance of repetition
  and contrast in music and how they might create this. They are introduced to the basic
  functions of DAW recording."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils develop their understanding of how music works, specifically the
  role of the kick and snare in drum grooves, the importance of the backbeat in pop music and
  the balance of unity and variety in music. They are introduced to the basic functions of DAW
  recording and quantising extending their understanding of rhythm and note durations through
  American notation terms. They consider phrasing from the perspective of a drum groove in
  contrast to melodic phrasing and the role the drummer or groove plays in an ensemble or piece
  of music.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-981-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-981-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-981-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-981-4 ;
  curric:id "981"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.085750Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-r ,
    oakcurric:thread-improvisation ,
    oakcurric:thread-drum-grooves ,
    oakcurric:thread-composing-and-improvising .

oakcurric:unit-984
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Fills and variation in RnB drum grooves"@en ;
  curric:slug "fills-and-variation-in-rnb-drum-grooves" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit develops pupil understanding of drum grooves, specifically how to create
  variation through adding embellishments around the basic rock groove. Pupils also learn
  about the fundamental shared features of pop music."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils develop their knowledge of drum grooves, specifically the use of
  upbeats in the kick, the open hi-hat function and how to use the toms appropriately. Pupils
  learn about the role of the fill in highlighting the phrase end and start to develop their
  ability to improvise within a bar (or half bar) of a given groove. They develop their
  understanding of DAW capabilities and learn to quantise to 1/8, developing their
  understanding of semiquavers.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-984-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-984-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-984-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-984-4 ;
  curric:id "984"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.120735Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-r ,
    oakcurric:thread-improvisation ,
    oakcurric:thread-daw ,
    oakcurric:thread-drum-grooves ,
    oakcurric:thread-composing-and-improvising .

oakcurric:unit-1009
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The sound of 90s grunge"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-role-of-improvision-harmony-and-rhythm-in-blues-composition" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to 90s Grunge music, including the context of the
  style and its other musical influences. Pupils learn about the main musical features and
  about extended pop song structure, riffs with power chords, harmonic rhythm and phrase
  structure in melody and lyric writing."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils extend their understanding of writing with chords, bass lines and
  drum grooves, specifically more creative use of the cymbals and drum fills and their
  understanding of unity and variety in successful composition within an extended pop
  structure. They learn about adapting an instrumental melody to a vocal melody to fit the
  rhythm of the words.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1009-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1009-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1009-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1009-4 ;
  curric:id "1009"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.136101Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-r ,
    oakcurric:thread-instrumental-fluency ,
    oakcurric:thread-improvisation ,
    oakcurric:thread-expressive-elements ,
    oakcurric:thread-composing-and-improvising .

oakcurric:unit-1001
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Orchestral melodies"@en ;
  curric:slug "orchestral-melodies" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit develops knowledge and understanding of the instruments of the
  orchestra. Pupils also learn to play a famous orchestral melody on the keyboard, learning
  to play and move out of position and they learn to identify from C to octave C on the
  stave through performance."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils continue to develop their performance and rehearsal skills and
  continue to develop keyboard fluency, learning to play out of position and across the whole C
  scale. They consolodate their skills of performing with both hands with a rhythmically simple
  left hand part and of using notation (crotchets, minims, semibreves and dotted rhythms) in
  performance. They extend their understanding of expressive elements, including how they can
  use emphasis, dynamics and tempo. They develop their listening skills, learning how the main
  orchestral instruments work, their main roles and their timbre.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1001-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1001-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1001-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1001-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1001-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1001-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1001-7 ;
  curric:id "1001"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.167734Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-melody ,
    oakcurric:thread-instrumental-fluency ,
    oakcurric:thread-expressive-elements .

oakcurric:unit-2599
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Minimalist composition"@en ;
  curric:slug "minimalist-composition" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit develops understanding of minimalism, including the context of the style
  and the main musical features used in creating minimalist compositions. Pupils compose and
  improvise in a minimalist style, including rhythmic and melodic patterns."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils are introduced to new ideas of creating variety within a
  fundamentally repetitive structure, particularly the use of ostinati, changing textures and
  minimalist techniques such as retrograde. They are introduced to improvising with pitch,
  using the pentatonic scale as a musical starting point and they develop their understanding
  of using a DAW for pitch as well as rhythmic composition. They reinforce their understanding
  of what makes a musical idea successful and continue to learn techniques for developing
  musical ideas.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2599-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2599-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2599-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-2599-4 ;
  curric:id "2599"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.182597Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 .

oakcurric:unit-1006
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Understanding samba"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-bass-hooks-and-grooves-of-80s-pop" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to Samba as a type of Brazilian dance and music,
  including batucada. They learn the context of the style and about the instruments,
  ensembles and features of the music, including polyrhythm and develop a Samba-style
  composition."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils develop their composition skills through composing with extended
  chords and bass lines, extending their understanding of harmony. They develop their
  improvisation skills through learning extended strategies for successful improvisation within
  a more complex melodic structure and scales and they continue to develop their ability to use
  a DAW creatively and bring different musical elements together (melody, harmony and rhythm)
  to show their understanding of how music works.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1006-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1006-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1006-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1006-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1006-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1006-6 ;
  curric:id "1006"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.200227Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-r ,
    oakcurric:thread-composing-and-improvising ,
    oakcurric:thread-drum-grooves ,
    oakcurric:thread-improvisation ,
    oakcurric:thread-harmony ,
    oakcurric:thread-daw .

oakcurric:unit-980
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Keyboard fundamentals"@en ;
  curric:slug "keyboard-fundamentals" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to the keyboard, providing them with a functional
  understanding to explore sound and apply musical concepts. They learn to perform short
  melodies, how to find and play in the C position and how to identify middle C to G on the
  stave through performance."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils continue to develop their performance skills and how to practise
  and rehearse. They start to develop keyboard fluency and extend their understanding of
  melodic shape and phrasing, learning simple approaches to performing with expression. They
  learn an ABA structured melody developing their sense of how music can be put together
  successfully.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-980-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-980-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-980-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-980-4 ;
  curric:id "980"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.233604Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-r ,
    oakcurric:thread-instrumental-fluency ,
    oakcurric:thread-expressive-elements .

oakcurric:unit-1101
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Film Music"@en ;
  curric:slug "film-music" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores film music and how composers use music to enhance mood,
  atmosphere and storytelling. Pupils study common film music techniques and themes, and
  apply this knowledge by composing and performing music to accompany visual scenes,
  developing their composition and performance skills."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils develop their understanding of composing to a stimulus, exploring
  thematic and motivic development and the impact of tonality and dissonance on mood. They
  develop their understanding of how musical elements and techniques shape mood and impact,
  learning about musical cliches and how orchestral instruments are used to create contrasting
  effects and support storytelling. They learn about leitmotif, continuing to develop their
  understanding of musical development.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1101-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1101-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1101-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1101-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1101-5 ;
  curric:id "1101"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.238823Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-composing-and-improvising .

oakcurric:unit-1000
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Reggaeton: from Puerto Rico to global phenomenon"@en ;
  curric:slug "recreating-the-sound-of-90s-grunge" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils are introduced to Reggaeton, including the context of the style and the
  influences. They learn about the dembow beat, the tresillo and hooks and riffs. They also
  develop their understanding of DAW capabilities including low-pass filter sweeps."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils develop their understanding of drum grooves,
  electronic dance music and how to create variation in music within a repetitive structure,
  extending their understanding of the importance of unity and variety in music. They develop
  their understanding of composing pop-syle bass lines and the importance of the tonic. They
  learn about the impact of the musical features on the overall effect and continue to develop
  their ability to use a DAW creatively.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1000-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1000-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1000-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1000-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1000-5 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1000-6 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1000-7 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1000-8 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-1000-9 ;
  curric:id "1000"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.318164Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-r ,
    oakcurric:thread-instrumental-fluency ,
    oakcurric:thread-drum-grooves ,
    oakcurric:thread-improvisation ,
    oakcurric:thread-harmony ,
    oakcurric:thread-daw ,
    oakcurric:thread-composing-and-improvising .

oakcurric:unit-3832
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Working out pop hooks and riffs by ear"@en ;
  curric:slug "working-out-pop-hooks-and-riffs-by-ear" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit focuses on developing pupils' ability to work out simple melodic ideas
  from modern pop and rock songs by ear. It introduces techniques for accurately recreating
  rhythm and pitch patterns, and also develops their understanding of how to recreate
  specific timbres accurately."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit, pupils develop their aural, performing and music technology
  skills. They learn to identify ascending and descending pitch by ear, recognise conjunct and
  disjunct melodic movement, and describe and match timbres. Pupils practise repeating
  syncopated and non-syncopated rhythms and utilise their drum groove understanding to work out
  specific drum patterns. They continue to develop their ability to use key DAW functions such
  as recording, quantising and selecting instruments.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3832-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3832-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3832-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3832-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3832-5 ;
  curric:id "3832"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.773734Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-music-key-stage-3 .

